<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
The male of this species is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wesołowska &amp; Azarkina &amp; Wiśniewski" authorityYear="2020" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Peplometus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peplometus nimba" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nimba">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Peplometus nimba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it can be identified by the presence of a big apical process on the first pair of legs and the metatarsus of this pair shorter than tibia (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 129–135" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figures 129 - 135. First leg of male 129 Pachyballus castaneus 130 Peplometus biscutellatus 131, 132 P. chlorophthalmus 133 P. congoensis 134 P. oyo 135 P. nimba 132 retrolateral view, others prolateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures129-135" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427075" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">134</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
